{"cursor":"7745","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n zones of the Earth where all twelve months have mean temperatures above 18 Â°C\n (64 Â°F).]]\n\nThe 'tropics' is a region of the Earth surrounding the Equator. It is limited in\nlatitude by the Tropic of Cancer in the northern hemisphere at approximately\n N and the Tropic of Capricorn in the southern hemisphere at  S; these\nlatitudes correspond to the axial tilt of the Earth. The tropics are also\nreferred to as the 'tropical zone' and the 'torrid zone' (see geographical\nzone). The tropics include all the areas on the Earth where the Sun reaches a\npoint directly overhead at least once during the solar year.\n\nThe tropics are distinguished from the other climatic and biomatic regions of\nEarth, the middle latitudes and the polar regions on either side of the\nequatorial zone.\n","linknr":292,"url":"Tropical","recorded":1362372925,"links":92,"instances":["meteorology"],"pdf":["http://www.hydrol-earth-syst-sci.net/11/1633/2007/hess-11-1633-2007.pdf","http://www.hydrol-earth-syst-sci.net/11/1633/2007/hess-11-1633-2007.pdf","http://www.cig.ensmp.fr/~iahs/redbooks/a140/iahs_140_0063.pdf"],"categories":["Tropics|","Seasons"],"headings":["Seasons and climate","Tropical ecosystems","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4a/World_map_torrid.svg/300px-World_map_torrid.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d1/Koppen_World_Map_Af_Am_Aw.png/300px-Koppen_World_Map_Af_Am_Aw.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/33/Monthly_zonal_mean_precipitation.png/220px-Monthly_zonal_mean_precipitation.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/Kota_Kinabalu_by_Dale_Preston.jpg